    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>In functional analysis, a "space" typically refers to a vector space equipped with additional structure, such as a topology, norm, or inner product. These structures provide a framework for studying functions as vectors and for analyzing limiting operations.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Common types of spaces in functional analysis include:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:strong>Vector spaces:</fr:strong> Sets equipped with operations of vector addition and scalar multiplication that satisfy certain axioms</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong><fr:link type="local" href="FA-000G.xml" addr="FA-000G" title="Metric Space">Metric spaces</fr:link>:</fr:strong> Sets equipped with a distance function (metric) that defines the concept of nearness between elements</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong><fr:link type="local" href="FA-0017.xml" addr="FA-0017" title="Normed vector space">Normed spaces</fr:link>:</fr:strong> Vector spaces equipped with a norm function that assigns a notion of length to vectors</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong><fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach spaces</fr:link>:</fr:strong> Complete normed vector spaces, where every Cauchy sequence converges</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong><fr:link type="local" href="FA-0012.xml" addr="FA-0012" title="Inner product space">Inner product spaces</fr:link>:</fr:strong> Vector spaces equipped with an inner product, which generalizes the dot product in Euclidean space</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong><fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert spaces</fr:link>:</fr:strong> Complete inner product spaces, combining the structures of Banach spaces and inner product spaces</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong>Topological vector spaces:</fr:strong> Vector spaces equipped with a topology compatible with the vector operations</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong>Locally convex spaces:</fr:strong> Topological vector spaces where the topology is defined by a family of seminorms</fr:li></fr:ul>
    <fr:p>Function spaces are particularly important in functional analysis. These are spaces whose elements are functions, such as:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:strong><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C(X)]]></fr:tex>:</fr:strong> The space of continuous functions on a topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex>:</fr:strong> The spaces of measurable functions whose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-th power is integrable</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^k]]></fr:tex>:</fr:strong> Sobolev spaces of functions with weak derivatives up to order <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
    <fr:p>The study of these spaces and the operators between them forms the core of functional analysis.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
