            <fr:title text="Lp space">Lp space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-002D.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E \subset  \mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable set</fr:link> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \in  [1, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex>. We call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}^p(E)]]></fr:tex> the set of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable</fr:link> functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: E \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> such that</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^p} < +\infty ]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Now, we set the following <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002B.xml" addr="FA-002B" title="Equivalence relation">equivalence relation</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}^p(E)]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f,g \in  \mathcal {L}^p(E)]]></fr:tex>. We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \sim  g]]></fr:tex> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x) = g(x)]]></fr:tex> for <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost every</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  E]]></fr:tex>. We set</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p(E) = \mathcal {L}^p(E)/\sim ]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p(E)]]></fr:tex> is the quotient (vector) <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}^p(E)]]></fr:tex> through the relation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sim ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>For a given <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0084">equivalence class</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[f] \in  L^p(E)]]></fr:tex>, we define the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0018.xml" addr="FA-0018" title="Norm">norm</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[f]]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^p(E)}]]></fr:tex> for an arbitrary representative <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \in  [f]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>From now on, by abuse of notation, we shall confuse <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[f]]]></fr:tex> and its representative <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>. The <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p(E)]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Note</fr:strong>: The elements of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> spaces are not individual functions in the strictest sense, but rather <fr:strong>equivalence classes of functions</fr:strong>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
